WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:05.840 --> 00:00:08.480
As in the struggle
against Nazi Germany.

2
00:00:08.640 --> 00:00:10.640
American strategy in
the war against Japan

3
00:00:10.800 --> 00:00:14.320
includes launching mass bombing
attacks against factories.

4
00:00:14.480 --> 00:00:18.200
military installations.
and cities.

5
00:00:18.360 --> 00:00:20.160
But the map of
the Asia-Pacific War

6
00:00:20.320 --> 00:00:22.160
covers enormous distances.

7
00:00:22.320 --> 00:00:25.640
A new. more powerful
bomber is needed.

8
00:00:25.800 --> 00:00:28.200
the B-29 Superfortress.

9
00:00:28.360 --> 00:00:31.040
Securing air bases
for these super-forts

10
00:00:31.200 --> 00:00:34.680
becomes a primary objective
for President Roosevelt

11
00:00:34.840 --> 00:00:36.880
and American military leaders.

12
00:00:38.600 --> 00:00:40.120
All Wars changed the world.

13
00:00:40.280 --> 00:00:42.040
but none of them
changed the world

14
00:00:42.200 --> 00:00:43.920
like the second World War did.

15
00:00:44.080 --> 00:00:48.320
Japan's on the march.
Germany's on the march.

16
00:00:48.480 --> 00:00:51.560
No-one can imagine the nightmare
they're about to unleash.

17
00:00:51.720 --> 00:00:53.800
the most destructive war
in human history.

18
00:00:54.600 --> 00:00:57.000
Suddenly the world
is turned upside down

19
00:00:57.160 --> 00:01:00.360
and all hell is let loose.

20
00:01:00.520 --> 00:01:04.160
The West is stunned by
the speed of the advance.

21
00:01:04.880 --> 00:01:08.240
You get the Allies
led by the big three:

22
00:01:08.400 --> 00:01:10.280
Roosevelt. Churchill. Stalin.

23
00:01:10.440 --> 00:01:14.920
Men who are dealing with
immensely complicated questions.

24
00:01:15.080 --> 00:01:19.320
It's the biggest military
operation of human history.

25
00:01:19.480 --> 00:01:21.200
The Allies have to
come together

26
00:01:21.360 --> 00:01:23.600
not just militarily
but industrial scale.

27
00:01:23.760 --> 00:01:25.720
It's a global perspective.

28
00:01:25.880 --> 00:01:27.480
They have to fight
in every climate

29
00:01:27.640 --> 00:01:30.480
from the Arctic
to the jungles of the Pacific

30
00:01:30.640 --> 00:01:35.280
to the deserts of Africa
and the depths of the ocean.

31
00:01:37.080 --> 00:01:39.600
But there was
no certainty of victory.

32
00:01:39.760 --> 00:01:42.920
It was going to be
a horrific bloodbath.

33
00:01:43.080 --> 00:01:44.840
We see humans
at their absolute worst.

34
00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:46.960
how they treat other
human beings.

35
00:01:47.120 --> 00:01:48.600
And we see them
at their absolute best.

36
00:01:48.760 --> 00:01:50.880
willing to give their lives
that others might live.

37
00:01:51.040 --> 00:01:54.400
World War II was a struggle
in which there could be

38
00:01:54.560 --> 00:01:58.320
one victor and one vanquished.

39
00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:06.074
Do you want subtitles for any video?
-=[ ai.OpenSubtitles.com ]=-

40
00:02:20.040 --> 00:02:21.360
For over two years.

41
00:02:21.520 --> 00:02:25.400
the United States has been
building the B-29 bomber.

42
00:02:25.560 --> 00:02:27.000
the Superfortress.

43
00:02:27.160 --> 00:02:29.480
When it's ready to roll
off the assembly line.

44
00:02:29.640 --> 00:02:32.800
the B-29 will be one of
the most potent weapons

45
00:02:32.960 --> 00:02:34.720
in the American arsenal.

46
00:02:34.880 --> 00:02:36.320
The B-29 Superfortress

47
00:02:36.480 --> 00:02:40.600
is the most expensive programme
in World War II.

48
00:02:40.760 --> 00:02:43.600
$3 billion to go ahead
and build an aircraft.

49
00:02:43.760 --> 00:02:47.680
The B-29 is a stunning
leap in aircraft technology.

50
00:02:49.400 --> 00:02:53.000
The B-29 will incorporate
a pressurised cabin.

51
00:02:53.160 --> 00:02:55.120
airborne radar.

52
00:02:55.280 --> 00:02:58.320
It has 10 miles of wiring.

53
00:02:58.480 --> 00:02:59.960
It had remote-controlled turrets.

54
00:03:00.120 --> 00:03:02.520
It had the most powerful engines
in the history of the world.

55
00:03:02.680 --> 00:03:06.200
But the critical thing
about the B-29 was range.

56
00:03:06.360 --> 00:03:09.520
It could carry bombs
farther. higher. faster

57
00:03:09.680 --> 00:03:12.200
than anything else that
had. not just been built.

58
00:03:12.360 --> 00:03:13.960
but ever imagined.

59
00:03:14.120 --> 00:03:16.720
The complexity
of its design. however.

60
00:03:16.880 --> 00:03:19.480
delays its manufacture.

61
00:03:19.640 --> 00:03:21.520
It's been
riddled with problems.

62
00:03:21.680 --> 00:03:23.720
It ends up behind schedule.

63
00:03:26.320 --> 00:03:28.080
Bombing the
Japanese home islands

64
00:03:28.240 --> 00:03:30.760
is a crucial part of
the American strategy

65
00:03:30.920 --> 00:03:32.640
in the Asia-Pacific War.

66
00:03:32.800 --> 00:03:34.160
Allied air commanders
wanna launch

67
00:03:34.320 --> 00:03:36.800
the same kind of
air offensive against Japan

68
00:03:36.960 --> 00:03:39.520
that they've been carrying out
against Germany.

69
00:03:39.680 --> 00:03:43.840
They wanna destroy factories.
shipyards. infrastructure.

70
00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:47.720
bring the Japanese war economy
to its knees.

71
00:03:47.880 --> 00:03:51.360
In addition to
strategic considerations.

72
00:03:51.520 --> 00:03:54.560
President Roosevelt understands
that the American people

73
00:03:54.720 --> 00:03:59.000
expect retribution
against the Japanese.

74
00:04:00.160 --> 00:04:03.840
If you'd have done a public
opinion survey of Americans.

75
00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:05.200
there was a palpable sense

76
00:04:05.360 --> 00:04:07.920
of wanting to get these
people back for Pearl Harbor.

77
00:04:08.080 --> 00:04:10.480
By 1943. it's payback time.

78
00:04:10.640 --> 00:04:12.960
And so the B-29
is going to become

79
00:04:13.120 --> 00:04:14.840
the first weapon system

80
00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:18.040
that can really attack
the Japanese homeland

81
00:04:18.200 --> 00:04:19.760
and military targets.

82
00:04:19.920 --> 00:04:22.640
The problem is. where
are your airfields going to be?

83
00:04:22.800 --> 00:04:26.880
They have to be within range
of the Japanese home islands.

84
00:04:27.040 --> 00:04:28.800
US Marines
have been fighting their way

85
00:04:28.960 --> 00:04:31.560
across the Pacific.
but it will take months

86
00:04:31.720 --> 00:04:34.280
before they can secure
an area suitable

87
00:04:34.440 --> 00:04:36.720
for launching B-29s.

88
00:04:36.880 --> 00:04:39.680
The B-29's got
a 1.600 mile combat range.

89
00:04:39.840 --> 00:04:41.920
So Roosevelt's looking
at several options

90
00:04:42.080 --> 00:04:43.480
as to where to base these things.

91
00:04:43.640 --> 00:04:46.160
They don't have
an island close enough.

92
00:04:46.320 --> 00:04:47.800
but they do have an ally

93
00:04:47.960 --> 00:04:50.680
within range of the
Japanese home islands.

94
00:04:50.840 --> 00:04:53.800
And that ally is
Chiang Kai-shek and China.

95
00:04:54.720 --> 00:04:56.960
Chiang Kai-shek
emerged as the leader

96
00:04:57.120 --> 00:05:00.560
of the Chinese
Nationalist Party in 1928.

97
00:05:00.720 --> 00:05:02.600
He's ruled China ever since.

98
00:05:02.760 --> 00:05:05.680
He is the
Generalissimo of China.

99
00:05:05.840 --> 00:05:08.680
He's a general.
but he's also a dictator.

100
00:05:08.840 --> 00:05:11.400
The problem he's got is
since the early 1930s.

101
00:05:11.560 --> 00:05:15.040
there is rising communism
under Mao Zedong.

102
00:05:15.200 --> 00:05:16.640
He's effectively
got a civil war.

103
00:05:16.800 --> 00:05:19.280
In addition
to internal conflict.

104
00:05:19.440 --> 00:05:22.160
China faces an external threat.

105
00:05:27.080 --> 00:05:30.360
Japan invaded China in 1937

106
00:05:30.520 --> 00:05:33.640
and seized Chiang's capital.
Nanking.

107
00:05:33.800 --> 00:05:37.120
as well as all major
Chinese coastal cities.

108
00:05:37.280 --> 00:05:41.440
The Japanese control
95% of China's industry.

109
00:05:41.600 --> 00:05:45.560
90% of China's railways.
half of China's population.

110
00:05:45.720 --> 00:05:48.240
They control a quarter to a third
of China's landmass.

111
00:05:48.400 --> 00:05:50.800
And they closed off
all the Chinese ports.

112
00:05:52.280 --> 00:05:54.520
Severed from
Chinese port cities.

113
00:05:54.680 --> 00:05:58.040
Chiang established
a new capital. Chungking.

114
00:05:58.200 --> 00:06:00.240
and constructed a route
that connected China

115
00:06:00.400 --> 00:06:05.480
to the port of Rangoon in
the British colony of Burma.

116
00:06:05.640 --> 00:06:08.800
Cut through more than 700 miles
of mountainous jungle terrain.

117
00:06:08.960 --> 00:06:10.960
the Burma Road was China's

118
00:06:11.120 --> 00:06:13.000
main route for receiving supplies.

119
00:06:13.160 --> 00:06:16.320
primarily from the United States.

120
00:06:17.400 --> 00:06:21.120
Until Japan seized Burma too.

121
00:06:25.480 --> 00:06:28.080
The final piece of
this Japanese imperial puzzle

122
00:06:28.240 --> 00:06:31.000
was the conquest
of Burma in 1942.

123
00:06:31.160 --> 00:06:33.200
The Japanese seized
the Burma Road

124
00:06:33.360 --> 00:06:35.920
and make it impossible
for the Allies

125
00:06:36.080 --> 00:06:38.760
to supply China's armies.

126
00:06:38.920 --> 00:06:41.240
The Chinese have
lost their umbilical.

127
00:06:41.400 --> 00:06:43.720
they've lost their artery.
all their supplies flowing in.

128
00:06:43.880 --> 00:06:46.720
Chiang Kai-shek
has maybe four million men

129
00:06:46.880 --> 00:06:50.880
available for military service.
but only a million rifles.

130
00:06:51.040 --> 00:06:54.840
So he's desperate for Western
material to flesh out his army

131
00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:58.640
and pose some kind of serious
obstacle to the Japanese.

132
00:07:05.080 --> 00:07:06.400
In November of 1943.

133
00:07:06.560 --> 00:07:08.840
President Roosevelt
confers with Chiang

134
00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:12.720
and British prime minister
Winston Churchill in Cairo.

135
00:07:14.440 --> 00:07:15.680
At the top of the agenda.

136
00:07:15.840 --> 00:07:19.000
how to keep
the Chinese in the fight.

137
00:07:19.160 --> 00:07:22.120
Franklin Roosevelt is worried
that if China is without resources.

138
00:07:22.280 --> 00:07:24.320
Chiang Kai-shek could make
a separate peace with Japan.

139
00:07:24.480 --> 00:07:26.800
which would be hugely
problematic for the Americans.

140
00:07:26.960 --> 00:07:29.880
China is where the vast
majority of the Japanese army

141
00:07:30.040 --> 00:07:32.160
is currently being tied up.

142
00:07:32.320 --> 00:07:33.760
And let's not forget
that Roosevelt

143
00:07:33.920 --> 00:07:36.760
has this big new weapon. the B-29s.

144
00:07:36.920 --> 00:07:39.400
He wants to base them
in Southern China.

145
00:07:39.560 --> 00:07:43.560
So keeping China in the war is
absolutely essential to FDR.

146
00:07:43.720 --> 00:07:46.960
Chiang goes to
Cairo with a big shopping list.

147
00:07:47.120 --> 00:07:50.760
He needs aircraft.
fuel. shells. guns.

148
00:07:50.920 --> 00:07:53.600
He'll take anything
that the Allies will give him.

149
00:07:53.760 --> 00:07:55.840
He's pretty desperate.

150
00:07:56.000 --> 00:07:58.520
Winston Churchill...
This is all a bit alarming to him.

151
00:07:58.680 --> 00:08:01.880
He just doesn't trust Chiang
Kai-shek in his bones.

152
00:08:02.040 --> 00:08:05.600
Chiang Kai-shek has
a reputation for being corrupt.

153
00:08:05.760 --> 00:08:07.160
not particularly reliable.

154
00:08:07.320 --> 00:08:11.120
There are valid concerns that
instead of using the supplies

155
00:08:11.280 --> 00:08:14.080
that FDR is promising
Chiang Kai-shek

156
00:08:14.240 --> 00:08:16.560
for the purposes
of fighting Japan.

157
00:08:16.720 --> 00:08:18.360
he might instead
hoard those supplies

158
00:08:18.520 --> 00:08:20.560
and then use them
to fight the communists.

159
00:08:20.720 --> 00:08:24.200
FDR knew he wasn't
running a boy scout troop.

160
00:08:24.360 --> 00:08:26.400
so he didn't examine too closely

161
00:08:26.560 --> 00:08:29.800
the morals of those
who shared his interests.

162
00:08:29.960 --> 00:08:33.320
That wasn't how you
could fight a global war.

163
00:08:33.480 --> 00:08:37.200
At Cairo. FDR and Chiang
agree that the Chinese

164
00:08:37.360 --> 00:08:39.440
will build runways for the B-29s

165
00:08:39.600 --> 00:08:44.280
and that the US will send
even more supplies to China.

166
00:08:45.160 --> 00:08:47.840
That requires mind-boggling
scales of logistics.

167
00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:50.880
For a single bullet to get
to a single Chinese rifle.

168
00:08:51.040 --> 00:08:54.160
it's gotta come from a factory.
let's say in the Midwest.

169
00:08:54.320 --> 00:08:57.080
So you send it
all the way across the Pacific.

170
00:08:57.240 --> 00:08:58.680
The British still hold India.

171
00:08:59.800 --> 00:09:03.760
so it would then
get into Calcutta.

172
00:09:03.920 --> 00:09:05.400
then be put onto a train.

173
00:09:05.560 --> 00:09:07.920
then sent up to Northeast India.

174
00:09:08.080 --> 00:09:11.720
and then fly them
over the Himalayas

175
00:09:11.880 --> 00:09:14.320
to the nationalists in China.

176
00:09:17.200 --> 00:09:19.000
Flying the
India-China ferry

177
00:09:19.160 --> 00:09:21.520
over the highest mountain range
in the world

178
00:09:21.680 --> 00:09:24.240
is extremely hazardous.

179
00:09:24.400 --> 00:09:27.960
The men ordered to do it
call it the Hump.

180
00:09:28.120 --> 00:09:30.360
Flying supplies into China

181
00:09:30.520 --> 00:09:33.560
is something that's never
been attempted on this scale.

182
00:09:33.720 --> 00:09:36.200
These were just
transport aircraft.

183
00:09:36.360 --> 00:09:40.520
but the missions were as challenging
as bomber raids over Germany.

184
00:09:42.960 --> 00:09:45.920
These aircraft are taking off
with incredibly high weights

185
00:09:46.080 --> 00:09:49.120
because we are trying to get
as many supplies in as we can.

186
00:09:50.640 --> 00:09:52.680
The route is only
about 500 miles.

187
00:09:52.840 --> 00:09:57.760
but the difficulty is the altitude.

188
00:09:57.920 --> 00:10:01.040
These pilots are flying
in unpressurised aircraft

189
00:10:01.200 --> 00:10:04.040
over peaks
that are 16.000 feet high.

190
00:10:04.200 --> 00:10:07.520
and then back down again
to their Chinese bases.

191
00:10:09.560 --> 00:10:11.160
Got this hot. moist air

192
00:10:11.320 --> 00:10:14.200
bubbling out of the Indian Ocean.

193
00:10:14.360 --> 00:10:18.560
meeting with this Siberian air
blowing down from Tibet.

194
00:10:20.360 --> 00:10:23.280
causing some of the most
difficult weather conditions

195
00:10:23.440 --> 00:10:24.920
on the planet.

196
00:10:26.880 --> 00:10:30.000
You get these incredible
changes in air pressure.

197
00:10:31.760 --> 00:10:33.280
Pilots who flew the Hump say

198
00:10:33.440 --> 00:10:34.840
the plane'd lurch 100 feet
in the air.

199
00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:37.320
and then drop 200 feet.
and lurch back up a 100 feet.

200
00:10:40.640 --> 00:10:43.280
It's hard to imagine
for the pilots who do it.

201
00:10:43.440 --> 00:10:45.720
The aircraft is proven
but not in these conditions.

202
00:10:45.880 --> 00:10:48.400
So every time they go up.
they're learning.

203
00:10:48.560 --> 00:10:52.200
But there's a cost to learning this
real time.

204
00:10:52.360 --> 00:10:55.480
594 aircraft are lost
and 1.500 aircrew.

205
00:11:06.320 --> 00:11:09.120
The problem is you
have to deliver 18 tons of fuel.

206
00:11:09.280 --> 00:11:12.480
and other supplies. to get one ton
of stuff to the Chinese army.

207
00:11:12.640 --> 00:11:14.600
It was a trickle
of what was needed.

208
00:11:14.760 --> 00:11:18.800
But China remains a priority
for President Roosevelt.

209
00:11:18.960 --> 00:11:20.240
There is another option.

210
00:11:20.400 --> 00:11:22.760
The Allies need to
reopen the Burma Road.

211
00:11:37.080 --> 00:11:40.280
By late 1943. China
has been at war with Japan

212
00:11:40.440 --> 00:11:44.720
for six years. engaging the
majority of the Japanese Army.

213
00:11:47.240 --> 00:11:50.160
President Roosevelt
and his military leaders

214
00:11:50.320 --> 00:11:51.960
are determined to defend China.

215
00:11:52.120 --> 00:11:57.440
including using B-29s to strike
the Japanese home islands.

216
00:11:57.600 --> 00:12:01.160
The US plans to build four
air bases around Chengdu

217
00:12:01.320 --> 00:12:04.040
that will accommodate the B-29.

218
00:12:04.200 --> 00:12:08.640
The B-29
Superfortress is a heavy bomber.

219
00:12:08.800 --> 00:12:11.200
And that means it needs a runway

220
00:12:11.360 --> 00:12:13.880
that's strong enough to land on.

221
00:12:14.040 --> 00:12:17.840
But the problem is there's
no way to bring in a bulldozer.

222
00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:21.000
or a truck. or heavy
equipment into China.

223
00:12:21.160 --> 00:12:23.760
They simply won't
fit in the aircraft

224
00:12:23.920 --> 00:12:25.320
that are flying over the Hump.

225
00:12:25.480 --> 00:12:28.480
But the upside for running a
bomber campaign out of China

226
00:12:28.640 --> 00:12:31.120
is that the Americans know
that they will have access

227
00:12:31.280 --> 00:12:34.680
to all the Chinese labour
they could ask for.

228
00:12:40.720 --> 00:12:42.880
Hundreds
of thousands of people

229
00:12:43.040 --> 00:12:46.160
grinding out a runway by hand.

230
00:12:46.320 --> 00:12:48.960
No bulldozers or
complicated machinery available.

231
00:12:49.120 --> 00:12:51.080
Only manpower and hard work.

232
00:12:51.240 --> 00:12:55.040
Just the sheer
scale of human labour.

233
00:12:55.200 --> 00:12:58.280
it looks like ancient history.

234
00:12:58.440 --> 00:13:01.920
Men. women. children.
pulling the rollers.

235
00:13:02.080 --> 00:13:06.040
working side by side.
Their country in jeopardy.

236
00:13:06.200 --> 00:13:08.800
Chinese civilians defend
against the Japanese

237
00:13:08.960 --> 00:13:11.320
any way they can.
building roads.

238
00:13:11.480 --> 00:13:15.280
constructing airfields.
loading supplies.

239
00:13:15.440 --> 00:13:17.840
China's an agrarian economy

240
00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:21.280
in a time period where industrial
warfare has taken over.

241
00:13:21.440 --> 00:13:24.320
So how do they produce all
these weapons that you need?

242
00:13:24.480 --> 00:13:26.040
For example. how do
you produce tanks?

243
00:13:26.200 --> 00:13:29.720
So part of the problem here for
Chiang is that he needs everything.

244
00:13:29.880 --> 00:13:33.760
The only way to bring
the tanks and the artillery

245
00:13:33.920 --> 00:13:35.680
that Chiang needs into China

246
00:13:35.840 --> 00:13:38.760
is to reopen the Burma Road.

247
00:13:38.920 --> 00:13:41.720
The Allies have more than
a quarter of a million troops

248
00:13:41.880 --> 00:13:46.240
based in Eastern India.
from Calcutta to Ledo in Assam.

249
00:13:46.400 --> 00:13:48.360
They plan
a two-pronged offensive.

250
00:13:48.520 --> 00:13:51.960
The British 14th Army
will push into Central Burma

251
00:13:52.120 --> 00:13:53.640
to expel the Japanese.

252
00:13:53.800 --> 00:13:56.800
An American-led force will
cross into Northern Burma

253
00:13:56.960 --> 00:14:02.440
and fight their way through to
re-establish the Burma Road.

254
00:14:02.600 --> 00:14:06.720
General Joseph Stilwell
commands the American forces.

255
00:14:06.880 --> 00:14:10.280
His personal and professional
connection to China

256
00:14:10.440 --> 00:14:12.160
spans three decades.

257
00:14:12.320 --> 00:14:15.400
Joseph Stilwell.
well known as Vinegar Joe.

258
00:14:15.560 --> 00:14:18.840
he's cranky. and acerbic.
and sarcastic.

259
00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:21.160
But Stilwell
speaks and reads Mandarin.

260
00:14:21.320 --> 00:14:22.680
He's a great lover of China

261
00:14:22.840 --> 00:14:26.080
and he has nothing but good
things to say about the Chinese.

262
00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:31.320
A respected Commander.

263
00:14:31.480 --> 00:14:35.240
Stilwell has trained thousands
of soldiers in his long career.

264
00:14:35.400 --> 00:14:38.960
Stilwell's task is to take
a handful of Chinese divisions.

265
00:14:39.120 --> 00:14:42.280
30.000 of Chiang Kai-shek's troops.

266
00:14:42.440 --> 00:14:45.080
and train them up to
Western standards.

267
00:14:48.040 --> 00:14:51.200
He takes over an old
British POW camp in India

268
00:14:51.360 --> 00:14:55.440
and he's able to give them
the training. the weaponry.

269
00:14:57.320 --> 00:15:02.240
so that they turn themselves
into relatively solid units.

270
00:15:03.880 --> 00:15:08.000
General William Slim.
Uncle Bill to his troops.

271
00:15:08.160 --> 00:15:11.560
leads the British 14th Army.
a multinational force

272
00:15:11.720 --> 00:15:15.680
comprised of units from
Britain. India. and Africa.

273
00:15:15.840 --> 00:15:18.040
Many have been
battling the Japanese

274
00:15:18.200 --> 00:15:20.920
since the invasion of Burma.

275
00:15:21.640 --> 00:15:24.560
Slim says. look.
we got beaten in Burma

276
00:15:24.720 --> 00:15:27.960
because we couldn't fight in the
jungle like the Japanese can.

277
00:15:28.120 --> 00:15:30.120
They're not superhuman.
We have to learn how to do it.

278
00:15:30.280 --> 00:15:33.400
The Japanese were considered
to be these amazing jungle fighters.

279
00:15:33.560 --> 00:15:36.680
But we should remember.
Japan's not a jungle country.

280
00:15:36.840 --> 00:15:39.400
They're not great jungle fighters
cos they grew up in it.

281
00:15:39.560 --> 00:15:41.320
This is about training.

282
00:15:41.480 --> 00:15:43.640
A complete rethink is needed.

283
00:15:43.800 --> 00:15:47.880
Slim starts training everybody.
not just frontline infantrymen.

284
00:15:48.040 --> 00:15:50.960
Everyone needs to be able to handle
themselves with their weapons.

285
00:15:51.120 --> 00:15:54.400
the bottle washers and the cooks
and the truck drivers.

286
00:15:54.560 --> 00:15:56.360
And everyone needs to
know that the Japanese

287
00:15:56.520 --> 00:15:58.240
are not these supermen.
They're not bogey men.

288
00:15:58.400 --> 00:16:01.360
Actually. they are
completely defeatable.

289
00:16:07.560 --> 00:16:10.280
So I think by this point. the
war's going very badly for Japan.

290
00:16:10.440 --> 00:16:14.080
You've had the Battle of Midway
in 1942.

291
00:16:15.160 --> 00:16:18.320
which Japan lost.

292
00:16:18.480 --> 00:16:19.800
Now. as a result.
Japanese shipping

293
00:16:19.960 --> 00:16:21.320
is struggling to get through.

294
00:16:21.480 --> 00:16:25.080
So you've got rationing
tightening in Japan.

295
00:16:25.240 --> 00:16:29.320
And then back in Europe. you've
had the German loss at Stalingrad.

296
00:16:29.480 --> 00:16:32.080
You've had the
toppling of Mussolini.

297
00:16:32.240 --> 00:16:34.680
So I think at this point.
Japan doesn't expect

298
00:16:34.840 --> 00:16:37.400
it's gonna get any help.
really. from the Axis powers.

299
00:16:38.520 --> 00:16:42.960
Hideki Tojo. who has
been Prime Minister since 1941.

300
00:16:43.120 --> 00:16:47.560
is the dominant force in the
Japanese government and military.

301
00:16:47.720 --> 00:16:51.160
By early 1944.
there's a feeling for Tojo

302
00:16:51.320 --> 00:16:52.840
and for others
at the high command

303
00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:54.760
something can be done
elsewhere in the war

304
00:16:54.920 --> 00:16:56.640
to try and offer Japan
a little bit of progress.

305
00:16:56.800 --> 00:16:59.440
And some kind of dramatic
success for the Japanese

306
00:16:59.600 --> 00:17:02.840
might force the Americans to
come to the negotiating table.

307
00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:05.200
One idea is to put some
pressure on the Allies

308
00:17:05.360 --> 00:17:09.960
in Northeast India and on
Chiang Kai-shek in China.

309
00:17:10.880 --> 00:17:15.120
Prime Minister Tojo
approves Operation U-Go.

310
00:17:15.280 --> 00:17:17.200
an invasion into India.

311
00:17:17.360 --> 00:17:19.440
His generals prepare to attack

312
00:17:19.600 --> 00:17:21.800
the British bases of the 14th Army

313
00:17:21.960 --> 00:17:26.040
and to capture the
American Hump airfields.

314
00:17:26.200 --> 00:17:29.040
Tojo understands
that at this point.

315
00:17:29.200 --> 00:17:30.680
these flights across the Hump

316
00:17:30.840 --> 00:17:33.840
are the last remaining
connection point with the West

317
00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:36.000
that the Chinese
national government has.

318
00:17:36.160 --> 00:17:39.120
And if you can cut
those air bases off.

319
00:17:39.280 --> 00:17:42.280
that will then be the straw
that breaks the nationalist back.

320
00:17:44.040 --> 00:17:48.240
For the Allies. this is rife
with portents of disaster.

321
00:18:05.160 --> 00:18:09.880
March 1944.
Operation U-Go begins.

322
00:18:10.040 --> 00:18:14.160
Japanese troops move across
the Burmese jungle into India.

323
00:18:14.320 --> 00:18:19.000
toward British bases and
the American airfields.

324
00:18:19.160 --> 00:18:22.840
The Japanese commander is
General Renya Mutaguchi.

325
00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:25.920
Mutaguchi thinks
he is a creature of destiny.

326
00:18:26.080 --> 00:18:29.280
And he's got a plan.
He believes that right there.

327
00:18:29.440 --> 00:18:33.120
on the very. very western
frontier of the Japanese Empire.

328
00:18:33.280 --> 00:18:37.320
he could strike a blow that
could save the war for Japan.

329
00:18:37.480 --> 00:18:38.920
Mutaguchi
hopes his invasion

330
00:18:39.080 --> 00:18:43.160
will inspire the Indians
to overthrow the British

331
00:18:43.320 --> 00:18:44.920
and join Japan in the war.

332
00:18:45.080 --> 00:18:48.040
The Japanese are banking
on speed and surprise.

333
00:18:48.200 --> 00:18:49.640
that they're gonna
move three divisions

334
00:18:49.800 --> 00:18:52.560
across these 8.000 foot high
mountains

335
00:18:52.720 --> 00:18:54.080
in the space of just a few days.

336
00:18:54.240 --> 00:18:59.360
As such. he cuts the rations
for all of his attack soldiers

337
00:18:59.520 --> 00:19:03.600
to just 20 days' worth of food.
- The Japanese soldiers

338
00:19:03.760 --> 00:19:08.760
carry a very small amount of
food supply. like dried rice.

339
00:19:08.920 --> 00:19:13.000
And they do not carry
many heavy weapons.

340
00:19:13.160 --> 00:19:15.640
So the Japanese
cannot get locked in

341
00:19:15.800 --> 00:19:18.280
to an attritional battle.
Cos they're travelling light.

342
00:19:18.440 --> 00:19:21.200
they're gonna have to rely on
capturing British supply dumps

343
00:19:21.360 --> 00:19:23.400
as they go along. It's a gamble.

344
00:19:25.800 --> 00:19:27.560
To get to the air bases
in India.

345
00:19:27.720 --> 00:19:31.280
Mutaguchi will need to
cross the Imphal Plain.

346
00:19:31.440 --> 00:19:34.560
site of a large
British forward base.

347
00:19:34.720 --> 00:19:38.600
The Imphal Plain. it's
got like a big river valley.

348
00:19:38.760 --> 00:19:41.160
surrounded by mountainous
jungley terrain.

349
00:19:41.320 --> 00:19:43.680
The Brits have used this
like a bread basket.

350
00:19:43.840 --> 00:19:46.840
They've got airfields there.
they've got supply dumps. food.

351
00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:49.920
everything the Japanese need.

352
00:19:50.080 --> 00:19:53.600
Based in Imphal are
three British-Indian divisions

353
00:19:53.760 --> 00:19:56.640
from General Slim's 14th Army.

354
00:19:56.800 --> 00:19:58.760
They're about to push
into enemy territory

355
00:19:58.920 --> 00:20:03.040
when they receive reports that
Mutaguchi's Japanese troops

356
00:20:03.200 --> 00:20:05.040
are moving towards them.

357
00:20:07.760 --> 00:20:11.120
Bill Slim's new plan
is to withdraw slightly.

358
00:20:11.280 --> 00:20:12.960
create a killing zone.

359
00:20:13.120 --> 00:20:16.800
let the Japanese attack
through this difficult terrain.

360
00:20:16.960 --> 00:20:20.440
and pound them
with artillery and aircraft.

361
00:20:20.600 --> 00:20:23.000
He's going to
relinquish ground.

362
00:20:23.160 --> 00:20:25.240
but all the time
he's going to attrit.

363
00:20:25.400 --> 00:20:27.840
grind down the Japanese.

364
00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:30.280
This is a high risk strategy

365
00:20:30.440 --> 00:20:33.680
and you can only do that if
you're extremely confident

366
00:20:33.840 --> 00:20:35.720
that your men are
sufficiently trained.

367
00:20:37.360 --> 00:20:40.720
But Mutaguchi's
force arrives quickly

368
00:20:40.880 --> 00:20:44.480
and is far larger than
Slim was expecting.

369
00:20:45.360 --> 00:20:47.400
So when these
Japanese divisions

370
00:20:47.560 --> 00:20:50.680
start sort of materialising
out of the jungle.

371
00:20:50.840 --> 00:20:52.920
it's a real pucker
moment for the British.

372
00:21:04.880 --> 00:21:10.720
The Japanese encircle Imphal
and cut off its supply roads.

373
00:21:10.880 --> 00:21:13.000
There is this just brutal battle.

374
00:21:13.160 --> 00:21:16.040
The fighting is
incredibly close quarter.

375
00:21:19.800 --> 00:21:22.880
And it is absolutely
touch and go.

376
00:21:27.960 --> 00:21:32.120
But Mutaguchi
is mired in mental models

377
00:21:32.280 --> 00:21:33.640
that were applicable in 1942

378
00:21:33.800 --> 00:21:36.720
but are no longer
applicable in '44.

379
00:21:36.880 --> 00:21:39.800
Back then. if you hit
an Indian division

380
00:21:39.960 --> 00:21:41.600
in the face with
a frontal attack.

381
00:21:41.760 --> 00:21:43.600
a lot of the time it fell apart.

382
00:21:43.760 --> 00:21:47.280
But Slim's army is better
trained. it is more resilient.

383
00:21:47.440 --> 00:21:51.560
and from a morale standpoint.
they believe in themselves.

384
00:21:51.720 --> 00:21:54.680
They think that they can
fight the Japanese toe to toe.

385
00:21:56.240 --> 00:21:59.160
Fighting is
relentless around Imphal.

386
00:21:59.320 --> 00:22:00.680
but General Slim has a plan

387
00:22:00.840 --> 00:22:02.960
to bring in reinforcements
and supplies.

388
00:22:05.200 --> 00:22:09.360
All this time. Imphal
itself is completely cut off.

389
00:22:09.520 --> 00:22:11.000
And if you're
gonna make a stand.

390
00:22:11.160 --> 00:22:12.920
you're gonna need supplies.

391
00:22:13.080 --> 00:22:16.200
What Slim recognises with
his American colleagues

392
00:22:16.360 --> 00:22:18.200
is that air power is
key to the whole thing.

393
00:22:20.280 --> 00:22:23.120
There's only one way to
supply this Allied pocket.

394
00:22:23.280 --> 00:22:25.120
and that is by air.

395
00:22:25.280 --> 00:22:26.960
The Americans
have already got

396
00:22:27.120 --> 00:22:30.960
a very efficient. well-trained
transport air force

397
00:22:31.120 --> 00:22:33.640
in the north of India. the Hump.

398
00:22:33.800 --> 00:22:36.960
And they turn that
airlift 90 degrees aside

399
00:22:37.120 --> 00:22:43.040
and aim it towards Imphal
and the British troops there.

400
00:22:44.520 --> 00:22:47.240
When you're
flying low and slow.

401
00:22:47.400 --> 00:22:50.000
you are one big fat target.

402
00:22:50.160 --> 00:22:53.240
These cargo planes have
no defensive armament.

403
00:22:53.400 --> 00:22:55.280
they don't have any guns.

404
00:22:55.440 --> 00:22:58.200
And if you push the cargo
out four seconds late.

405
00:22:58.360 --> 00:23:00.120
it's gonna end up
in Japanese hands.

406
00:23:01.520 --> 00:23:04.000
But astonishingly it works.

407
00:23:06.360 --> 00:23:08.440
These transports
airdrop and land

408
00:23:08.600 --> 00:23:12.280
about 14 million pounds
of food. ammunition.

409
00:23:12.440 --> 00:23:15.480
heavy equipment. and
thousands of fresh troops.

410
00:23:15.640 --> 00:23:19.760
And that means that Slim can
keep his forces fighting.

411
00:23:22.040 --> 00:23:25.800
Mutaguchi had hoped to
take Imphal within days.

412
00:23:25.960 --> 00:23:28.680
right off the march. Instead.
what he gets is a meat grinder.

413
00:23:34.760 --> 00:23:38.080
For weeks. divisions
of General Slim's 14th Army

414
00:23:38.240 --> 00:23:41.840
have been receiving
supplies by air.

415
00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:47.080
They're the frontline resisting
Japan's invasion of India.

416
00:23:53.760 --> 00:23:56.560
But Mutaguchi's men
are running out of time.

417
00:23:56.720 --> 00:23:58.880
The Japanese
have gone into the offensive

418
00:23:59.040 --> 00:24:00.360
without much equipment.

419
00:24:00.520 --> 00:24:02.280
They don't have an
established supply line.

420
00:24:02.440 --> 00:24:05.520
So every day that they
don't achieve success.

421
00:24:05.680 --> 00:24:07.360
it becomes more
and more desperate.

422
00:24:07.520 --> 00:24:10.040
Of course. the
big problem they face is rations.

423
00:24:10.200 --> 00:24:13.280
They start to run out. hunger
starts to become a big issue.

424
00:24:13.440 --> 00:24:16.720
They're picking up snakes.
they're trying to eat monkeys.

425
00:24:16.880 --> 00:24:18.840
They are literally starving.

426
00:24:20.400 --> 00:24:25.560
General Tojo
famously issued instructions

427
00:24:25.720 --> 00:24:28.560
for the soldiers in the battlefield

428
00:24:28.720 --> 00:24:33.360
that to be taken by enemy
as a prisoner of war

429
00:24:33.520 --> 00:24:35.760
is unacceptable.

430
00:24:35.920 --> 00:24:41.760
Facing defeat. they should
make a final suicidal charge

431
00:24:41.920 --> 00:24:45.600
and die. or commit suicide.

432
00:24:47.680 --> 00:24:51.480
The survivors
are forced to retreat.

433
00:24:51.640 --> 00:24:55.080
Japanese soldiers are
dropping dead along the route.

434
00:24:55.240 --> 00:24:57.840
The retreat
becomes hellish.

435
00:24:58.000 --> 00:25:01.560
The Japanese words were
translated as the road of bones.

436
00:25:01.720 --> 00:25:04.920
The survivors' accounts
are of mass suicides

437
00:25:05.080 --> 00:25:06.880
all along the way.

438
00:25:07.040 --> 00:25:10.160
There are stories of Japanese
buddies getting together

439
00:25:10.320 --> 00:25:11.800
and hugging each other

440
00:25:11.960 --> 00:25:15.240
and then detonating a grenade
between the two of them.

441
00:25:17.240 --> 00:25:19.440
Up to this point in the war.

442
00:25:19.600 --> 00:25:22.200
this is the largest defeat
the Japanese Army

443
00:25:22.360 --> 00:25:26.280
has ever suffered on the ground.
around 60.000 casualties.

444
00:25:26.440 --> 00:25:28.840
Mutaguchi had
a vision of this operation

445
00:25:29.000 --> 00:25:32.160
to destroy the Allied efforts
in Northeastern India

446
00:25:32.320 --> 00:25:34.400
and foment an insurrection.

447
00:25:34.560 --> 00:25:38.640
All of those dreams are
shattered at the end of this.

448
00:25:43.520 --> 00:25:44.920
In the spring of 1944.

449
00:25:45.080 --> 00:25:48.200
President Roosevelt is
focused on Operation Overlord.

450
00:25:48.360 --> 00:25:50.600
the upcoming
invasion of Normandy.

451
00:25:50.760 --> 00:25:54.760
But he's frustrated by
the delays in East Asia

452
00:25:54.920 --> 00:25:58.960
and the fact that the B-29s
are still not in action.

453
00:25:59.120 --> 00:26:02.480
America is in Burma
and in this theatre

454
00:26:02.640 --> 00:26:04.360
to supply China with weapons

455
00:26:04.520 --> 00:26:07.560
and to supply their B-29
bases in Southern China.

456
00:26:07.720 --> 00:26:12.080
Roosevelt has been told time
and again by his military men

457
00:26:12.240 --> 00:26:13.920
that they're devoting
precious resources

458
00:26:14.080 --> 00:26:17.520
on an effort that looks
increasingly futile.

459
00:26:19.240 --> 00:26:23.480
And yet Roosevelt simply doesn't
see another horse to back.

460
00:26:23.640 --> 00:26:27.400
In May of 1944.
there is no alternate place

461
00:26:27.560 --> 00:26:30.600
from which B-29 bombers
can operate.

462
00:26:32.840 --> 00:26:36.480
In Northern Burma.
General Vinegar Joe Stilwell

463
00:26:36.640 --> 00:26:40.560
is preparing troops to
push to the Burma Road.

464
00:26:41.360 --> 00:26:44.000
If the Americans
can reopen that road.

465
00:26:44.160 --> 00:26:45.640
it's gonna completely transform

466
00:26:45.800 --> 00:26:48.520
not only the ground campaign
in China for Chiang

467
00:26:48.680 --> 00:26:52.480
but also the aerial campaign
for the American B-29s

468
00:26:52.640 --> 00:26:54.200
that are gonna be based in China.

469
00:26:54.360 --> 00:26:57.160
because they will be able to
drive over the heavy equipment

470
00:26:57.320 --> 00:26:59.120
that they can't fly
across the Hump.

471
00:26:59.280 --> 00:27:00.920
like steam shovels
and steam rollers.

472
00:27:01.080 --> 00:27:03.760
And so it'll transform these
bases into the sort of bases

473
00:27:03.920 --> 00:27:05.600
that Americans like to build.

474
00:27:05.760 --> 00:27:09.240
big. sprawling. and
full of warehouses.

475
00:27:11.560 --> 00:27:15.600
Stilwell's plan is to
move across Northern Burma.

476
00:27:15.760 --> 00:27:18.960
attack the Japanese
military base at Myitkyina.

477
00:27:19.120 --> 00:27:24.600
then push forward to create a
new route to the Burma Road.

478
00:27:27.400 --> 00:27:30.800
He sent 7.000 men.
including Chinese troops.

479
00:27:30.960 --> 00:27:34.040
and a veteran American
deep penetration force

480
00:27:34.200 --> 00:27:35.720
nicknamed Merrill's Marauders.

481
00:27:35.880 --> 00:27:40.080
on a three-week march through
the jungle towards Myitkyina.

482
00:27:40.920 --> 00:27:43.000
Certain fighting
environments kill you

483
00:27:43.160 --> 00:27:46.440
all by themselves. You don't need
bullets. you don't need shells.

484
00:27:46.600 --> 00:27:48.240
The jungle kills you.

485
00:27:48.400 --> 00:27:50.880
It destroys armies day by day.

486
00:27:51.040 --> 00:27:53.800
The American and
Chinese troops inserted there.

487
00:27:53.960 --> 00:27:56.160
they're just absolutely
devastated by illness.

488
00:27:56.320 --> 00:28:00.160
They've all got amoebic dysentery.
severe diarrhoea.

489
00:28:00.320 --> 00:28:04.120
They've all got. you know.
dengue and other tropical fevers.

490
00:28:04.280 --> 00:28:06.840
There was nowhere to rest.
there was nowhere to recuperate.

491
00:28:07.000 --> 00:28:09.680
and nowhere to get
the resources for war.

492
00:28:16.560 --> 00:28:18.520
On May 17th.
Stilwell's troops

493
00:28:18.680 --> 00:28:20.400
launched the attack
on Myitkyina.

494
00:28:26.520 --> 00:28:27.760
It's a hard-fought battle.

495
